<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-243-736  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 243 736.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Digital Review  March 12 1990 v7 n10 p1(2)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Cahners-Ziff Publishing Associates LP 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Interleaf lets users create 'active' documents. (the TFSelectronic publishing software enhanced with intelligent compounddocument features)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Ballou, Melinda-Carol.andM;</AUTHOR><SUMMARY>Interleaf demonstrated a version of its TFS electronic publishingsoftware at the Seybold Technology Forum that is able to retrievedata from across a network, integrate the data and place it in amanager's account on a VAX where it recognizes functions requiredand performs them.andP;  Interleaf's toolkit allows objects to beprogrammed that create 'active' documents; it will be available bythe 4th qtr of 1990, according to the company.andP;  These documentsare object oriented to allow them to go to different environmentsor different desktops in the same computing environment andmaintain their intelligence.andP;  Thus systems administrators need notbe asked to call in files when wanting to send documents around agroup.andP;  The technology was developed using Common Lisp; it willinclude a debugger, programming editor, sample utilities, a helpsystem and support; TFS costs from $2,000 to $15,000.andM;</SUMMARY><DESCRIPT>Company:   Interleaf Inc. (product enhancement).andO;Ticker:    LEAF.andO;Product:   TFS (Document processing system) (product enhancement).andO;Topic:     Software PackagesEnhancementsInformation Storage and RetrievalDocument Management SystemsElectronic PublishingProduct DevelopmentObject-Oriented ProgrammingProgram Development Tools.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>Interleaf lets users create 'active' documentsandM;BOSTON -- Imagine this: With a single command, a document on your workstationautomatically reaches across a network to retrieve data from a database,integrates that data within itself, and then zips off to your manager'saccount on a VAX, where it again recognizes other functions that need to beperformed and does them.andM;This isn't Walt Disney's Desktop Sorcerer's Apprentice.andP;  It's a newtechnology demonstrated by Interleaf last week at the Seybold TechnologyForum that builds this level of compound document intelligence intoInterleaf's TFS electronic publishing software.andM;Interleaf has developed a tool kit that allows users to program objects tocreate &quot;active&quot; documents.andP;  The tool kit will be launched officially thissummer and will be available by the fourth quarter, Interleaf officials said.andM;&quot;One of the things we're showing is a document on a Sun [workstation] thatruns a query to a database and brings information into that document,&quot; saidDavid Weinberger, Interleaf's director of strategic marketing.andP;  &quot;That datathen drives a Gantt chart showing the critical path of the project.andM;&quot;When the user closes the document, the document knows that it needs to senditself across the network to somebody on a DECstation 3100,&quot; he said.andP;  &quot;Whenthat person gets it, the document knows to run a different query on Ingres todrive the Gantt chart again.&quot;andM;Interleaf's active documents are object-oriented, so that the same documentcan go to different environments or to different desk tops within the samecomputing environment and carry the intelligence with it, according toWeinberger.andP;  &quot;This means that you can send around these documentsautomatically without asking a systems administrator to call in files foryou,&quot; he said.andM;&quot;It extends substantially what publishing software can do,&quot; said DavidBoucher, Interleaf's CEO.andP;  &quot;Programmers can take this and create to meet thespecific needs of users.andP;  You might have a special application where you needto follow a set of rules to meet CALS requirements, and build them in so thedocument will automatically comply.&quot;andM;Interleaf developed the technology using Common Lisp.andP;  &quot;Developing on Lispeased our cross-platform issues,&quot; Weinberger said.andM;The development kit for active documents will include a debugger, programmingeditor, set of useful functions, sample utilities, help system and support,he said.andM;TFS is priced from $2,000 to $15,000.andM;Interleaf Inc. is located at 10 Canal Park, Cambridge, MA 02141, (617)577-9813.andO;</TEXT></DOC>